    <body>
      <div xml:id="KT272-kilavi">
        <p type="edition">kaḻaṟiya pāṅkaṟkuk kiḻavaṉ uraittatu. </p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Told by HIM to the companion who urged [him]. </p>
      </div>

      <div xml:id="KT272">
        <lg type="edition">
          <l> tīṇṭalu miyaivatu kollō māṇṭa</l>
          <l> villuṭai vīḷaiyar kalliṭu peṭutta</l>
          <l> naṉantalaik kāṉat tiṉantalaip pirinta</l>
          <l> puṉkaṇ maṭamā ṉērpaṭat taṉṉaiyar</l>
          <l> cilaimāṇ kaṭuvicaik kalainiṟat taḻuttik</l>
          <l> kurutiyoṭu paṟitta ceṅkōl vāḷi</l>
          <l> māṟukoṇ ṭaṉṉa vuṇkaṇ</l>
          <l> ṇāṟiruṅ kūntaṟ koṭicci tōḷē.</l>
        </lg>

        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
          <l>Would it be enjoyable also to hold <note place="foot">T.V.G. understands an implication
            that HE has already had connection with HER, taking the <term xml:lang="ta">tīṇṭalum
            iyaivatu</term> to mean "will there be an opportunity to touch again" the shoulder.</note>
          </l>
          <l rend="indent">the shoulder of the creeper woman with fragrant dark tresses</l>
          <l rend="indent">[and] collyrium eyes, hostile like <note place="foot">Cām. understands
            that the eyes are opposed to each other like arrows (or something like this), but would
            that fit to the further image? T.V.G. explains the eyes to be sharp as arrows, which
            would weaken the connection even more.</note> red-stemmed arrows,</l>
          <l rend="indent2">pulled out with the blood of the lightning-quick <note place="foot">
              <term xml:lang="ta">kaṭu vicai</term> : is this an intensifying synonym compound?</note>
            monkey <note place="foot">Cām./T.V.G. take here the <term xml:lang="ta">kalai </term> to
            be the male of the deer and the <term xml:lang="ta">māṉ</term> of line 4 as its female,
            thus deriving one of the common images of separated couples. But <term xml:lang="ta">
            kalai</term> usually denotes a male monkey and māṉ usually denotes a male deer (although
            one might argue that the attribute <term xml:lang="ta">maṭam</term> which commonly is
            applied to females gives a hint to understand it that way). If we take the beginning
            seriously, that is, in the sense that HE has not yet touched HER shoulders, then the
            image of the monkey coming by chance in the way of the hunters who are actually after
            deer would make sense.</note>
          </l>
          <l rend="indent3">after hitting [his] vital spot, <note place="foot">
              <term xml:lang="ta">niṟattu aḻutti</term> most probably refers to the hunter hitting
            the "vital spot" of the animal (cf. NA 165.1).</note> [arrows] of resounding glory <note place="foot">It seems to make more sense to connect <term xml:lang="ta"> cilai māṇ </term>
            with <term xml:lang="ta">vāḷi</term> , although they are quite far apart, but of course
            it could also be a further attribute of the <term xml:lang="ta">kalai</term> , or a
            qualification of its quickness.</note>
          </l>
          <l rend="indent4">of her kin, [bearers] of famed bows, who,</l>
          <l rend="indent8">whistling, lift [and] aim stones</l>
          <l rend="indent5">to hit the sorrowful inexperienced stag</l>
          <l rend="indent5">which is separated from [its] group in the vast forest area?<note place="foot">The impact of this complicated image is presumably that SHE is well
            protected and HE ponders his chances. But how to understand the syntax? I take <term xml:lang="ta">aiyar</term> as a possessive genitive to <term xml:lang="ta">vāḷi</term>
            , and accordingly as the subject of lines 2-4, and <term xml:lang="ta">vīḷaiyar</term>
            as an apposition to <term xml:lang="ta">aiyar.</term> </note>
          </l>


        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
